    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv into memory and keep them in kernel variables for later steps. For each file, return a compact overview (do not print full tables):\n1) total row count; 2) minimum timestamp and maximum timestamp; 3) number of unique cmdb_id and list the top 20 cmdb_id values by frequency; 4) number of unique KPI/trace/log names and list the top 20 such names (use kpi_name for metric.csv, trace_name for trace.csv, log_name for log.csv, and for error_logs.csv list distinct message samples up to 20). Additionally for metric.csv only: list the top 10 cmdb_id by row count and for each of these show up to 10 distinct kpi_name values. Limit all returned lists to at most 20 items. Keep outputs as compact text/JSON. Do not convert timestamps to datetimes. Store the loaded DataFrames in kernel variables for subsequent steps."
}

{
    "analysis": "The previous step computed global P95/P5 for each (cmdb_id,kpi) and flagged every in-window point where value >= P95 or <= P5 as anomalous. The anomaly count is very large (121,770) and nearly all points for many groups are flagged because those groups are constant-valued (P95 == P5 == observed value). Those constant-series anomalies are likely false positives. To locate real faults we must (1) aggregate anomalies into consecutive anomalous sub-series (fault candidates), (2) compute severity of each candidate (how far the sub-series extremal deviates from the threshold), and (3) filter out trivial/short candidates (e.g., constant-equals-threshold or very short spikes). This will produce a manageable list of genuine fault candidates to inspect with traces/logs.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the kernel-stored anomaly table and thresholds, aggregate anomalies into consecutive anomalous sub-series (per cmdb_id + kpi_name) within the incident window. For each sub-series (fault candidate) compute: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_type (high / low / both), start_timestamp (min ts), end_timestamp (max ts), length_in_points, max_value_in_series, min_value_in_series, P95, P5, breach_high_pct = (max_value_in_series - P95) / max(abs(P95), 1e-9), breach_low_pct = (P5 - min_value_in_series) / max(abs(P5), 1e-9). Then filter the candidates keeping only those where length_in_points >= 3 AND (breach_high_pct > 0.5 OR breach_low_pct > 0.5). Return a compact summary (top 20) ordered by earliest start_timestamp (showing the columns above plus a severity_score = max(breach_high_pct, breach_low_pct) and anomaly_types_present). Also return the total number of candidates before and after filtering. Store the resulting candidates table in a kernel variable for the next step."
}
